        <article class="research-paper">
            <h1>Understanding Vaccines and Immunization</h1>

            <div class="article-content">
                <section class="intro-section">
                    <p class="lead-paragraph">
                        Vaccines are one of medicine's greatest achievements, preventing millions of deaths worldwide.
                        This guide explains vaccine science, recommended schedules, and addresses common concerns.
                        Stay protected through life with up-to-date immunization knowledge.
                    </p>
                </section>

                <section class="main-content">
                    <h2>How Vaccines Work</h2>
                    <p>
                        Vaccines train the immune system to recognize and combat pathogens without causing illness.
                        They contain antigens - harmless pieces of viruses or bacteria that stimulate antibody
                        production.
                        Memory cells remain in the body, providing long-term protection against future infections.
                    </p>

                    <h2>Childhood Immunization</h2>
                    <p>
                        The CDC recommends vaccinations against 16 diseases by age 18. Key vaccines include:
                    <ul class="medical-list">
                        <li>DTaP (Diphtheria, Tetanus, Pertussis)</li>
                        <li>MMR (Measles, Mumps, Rubella)</li>
                        <li>Polio</li>
                        <li>Hepatitis B</li>
                    </ul>
                    Follow the recommended schedule to ensure optimal protection during vulnerable developmental stages.
                    </p>

                    <h2>Adult Vaccinations</h2>
                    <p>
                        Immunity from childhood vaccines can wane, and new risks emerge with age. Essential adult
                        vaccines include:
                    <ul class="medical-list">
                        <li>Flu (annual)</li>
                        <li>Tdap/Td boosters (every 10 years)</li>
                        <li>Shingrix (shingles)</li>
                        <li>Pneumococcal (65+)</li>
                    </ul>
                    Travel vaccines and occupational requirements should also be considered.
                    </p>

                    <h2>Vaccine Safety</h2>
                    <p>
                        All vaccines undergo rigorous testing through multiple trial phases before approval. Common side
                        effects
                        like soreness or mild fever are normal immune responses. Severe reactions are extremely rare (1
                        in million
                        doses). Continuous monitoring through VAERS ensures ongoing safety surveillance.
                    </p>

                    <h2>Special Considerations</h2>
                    <p>
                        Immunocompromised individuals may need adjusted schedules. Live vaccines (MMR, Varicella) are
                        generally
                        avoided during pregnancy. Discuss allergies (e.g., egg, latex) with your provider. Catch-up
                        schedules
                        exist for missed childhood vaccines - it's never too late to vaccinate.
                    </p>
                </section>
            </div>
        </article>

